        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Building dreams</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Originally, LEGO did not manufacture the iconic plastic bricks</strong>. Instead, founder Ole Kirk Kristiansen, a carpenter by trade, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-03-2025-produced-wooden-toys" target="_blank">produced wooden toys</a>. The shift to plastic began in the 1940s with the advent of injection molding technology. During this time, he encountered a British company, Kiddicraft, which had developed small interlocking plastic cubes called “Kiddicraft Self-Locking Bricks.”
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/ben-jerrys-flavor-graveyard-vermont-discontinued-ice-cream-tombstones.png" alt="Employees in the LEGO woodworking factory" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Employees in the LEGO woodworking factory. Credits: lego website 
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Recognizing their potential, LEGO launched its version in 1949, branding them “<strong>Automatic Binding Bricks</strong>.” The defining moment came in 1955 with the introduction of the “<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-03-2025-lego-system-in-play" target="_blank">LEGO System in Play</a>.” According to the system, all elements should fit together, can be used in multiple ways, and can be built together. Retailers were given specific instructions on promoting this concept, ensuring customers understood its unique value.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>The first product to embrace this system was the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/bh-01-03-2025-town-plan-no-1-model" target="_blank">Town Plan No. 1 model</a></strong>, a collaborative effort with the Danish Road Safety Council. The set featured a stylized map, miniature vehicles, road signs, and even tiny police officers. It allowed children to build and navigate their urban environments while fostering creativity, critical thinking, and cooperative play.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

