      <mj-spacer height="14px" />
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Engineering play-time</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Despite LEGO's growing popularity, <strong>one fundamental issue remained: stability</strong>. Early interlocking bricks were prone to collapsing when stacked into taller structures. Determined to fix this, they developed the famous “<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-03-2025-stud-and-tube" target="_blank">stud-and-tube</a>” coupling mechanism in 1958. <strong>Adding cylindrical studs on the top of each brick and hollow tubes underneath</strong> significantly improved stability, making constructions sturdier and more versatile. <strong>This innovation was patented</strong>, securing LEGO’s dominance in the market.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Recognizing that traditional LEGO bricks posed a <strong>choking hazard for younger children</strong>, the company introduced <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-03-2025-duplo-bricks" target="_blank">Duplo bricks</a> in 1969. These larger bricks were <strong>twice the size of regular bricks</strong> in all dimensions yet remained fully compatible with traditional sets. The company actively marketed its products to both genders, ensuring a vast consumer base.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Another game-changing development was the <strong>introduction of the LEGO wheel</strong>. This innovation unlocked newer possibilities, allowing them to create various moving parts that added complexity to the structures. Their adaptability meant that <strong>kids weren’t just playing; they were engineering</strong>.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Lost and found</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Between 1994 and 2004, LEGO faced a period of financial instability, nearly reaching bankruptcy with ​​a debt load of over $800 Mn</strong>. Rapid global expansion, excessive diversification, and modernization efforts pushed costs far higher. The company invested heavily in sophisticated machinery while increasingly complex theme sets demanded advanced manufacturing processes. At the same time, electronic gaming surged in popularity, and competition for shelf space in toy stores intensified.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/legoland-billund-resort-first-park-lego-factory-denmark.png" alt="Legoland Billund Resort, the first Legoland park, opened near the original Lego factory in Billund, Denmark" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Legoland Billund Resort, the first Legoland park, opened near the original Lego factory in Billund, Denmark. Credits: legoland 
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">To cut expenses, they <strong>outsourced the production of less technical pieces</strong>. However, two game-changing strategies ultimately helped LEGO survive and thrive: <strong>licensing intellectual properties</strong> and <strong>crowdsourcing innovation</strong>. They merged its iconic bricks with beloved pop culture brands by securing licenses with powerhouse franchises like <strong><i>Star Wars</i></strong>, <strong><i>Harry Potter</i></strong>, and <strong><i>Winnie the Pooh</i></strong> for Duplo. The <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-03-2025-star-wars-franchise" target="_blank"><i>Star Wars franchise</i></a>, in particular, played a crucial role in <strong>reviving sales by 500% more than forecast measures</strong>.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The most revolutionary shift came through <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-01-03-2025-crowdsourcing" target="_blank">crowdsourcing</a>. <strong>This enabled users to submit their own designs for potential LEGO sets</strong>. Projects that received at least 10,000 community votes would be considered for production. This approach turned LEGO fans into active contributors, encouraging them to promote their designs while expanding LEGO’s reach. These measures ensured its rebound from near bankruptcy and established its identity as an innovator in the toy industry.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
